Several Mermaid Model Context Protocol (MCP) servers are available, all of which use the Mermaid CLI or Puppeteer to validate and render diagrams into formats like SVG or PNG [1][2][3][4][5]. While implementations vary by programming language (Node.js, Python, or Java) and configuration, they generally provide tools for syntax validation and image generation [1][3][6][7].

To set one up, you typically install the package (often via npm or npx) and add the server configuration to your MCP client's settings file (e.g., Claude Desktop or VS Code) [1][2][8][5].

Example configuration for a Node.js-based server:
```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "mermaid-server": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "package-name-here"]
    }
  }
}
```

Key features across these servers include theme customization, background color selection, and multiple output formats [4][6][5]. Some servers allow saving files directly to disk, while others return base64-encoded image data for direct use in chat [3][5].
